{
  "What does a capacitor store?": "",
  "Electrical energy in an electric field": "",
  "Magnetic energy stored in a coil of wire": "",
  "Kinetic energy of flowing electrons": "",
  "Charge on a single conducting plate": "",
  "A capacitor stores electrical energy in the electric field between its plates.": "",
  "What is capacitance?": "",
  "C = QV": "",
  "C = V/Q": "",
  "C = Q/V": "",
  "C = Q²/V": "",
  "Capacitance C = Q/V measures a capacitor's ability to store charge per unit voltage.": "",
  "What is the SI unit of capacitance?": "",
  "Volt (V)": "",
  "Henry (H)": "",
  "Farad (F)": "",
  "Coulomb (C)": "",
  "The SI unit of capacitance is the Farad (F). 1 F = 1 C/V.": "",
  "How does inserting a dielectric affect capacitance?": "",
  "Makes it zero": "",
  "No effect": "",
  "Increases it": "",
  "Decreases it": "",
  "A dielectric material between the plates increases capacitance by reducing the electric field and allowing more charge to be stored.": "",
  "How do capacitors combine in parallel?": "",
  "C_total = C₁ + C₂": "",
  "C_total = C₁ × C₂": "",
  "C_total = C₁ − C₂": "",
  "1/C_total = 1/C₁ + 1/C₂": "",
  "Capacitors in parallel add directly: C_total = C₁ + C₂ + ... This is opposite to how resistors combine.": "",
  "Energy stored in a capacitor:": "",
  "E = ½CV²": "",
  "E = CV": "",
  "E = 2CV²": "",
  "E = C²V": "",
  "Energy stored: U = ½CV² = ½QV = Q²/(2C).": "",
  "If plate separation d is halved, capacitance:": "",
  "Stays the same": "",
  "Doubles": "",
  "Quadruples": "",
  "Halves": "",
  "C = ε₀A/d. Halving d doubles C.": "",
  "How do capacitors combine in series?": "",
  "C_total = C₁ + C₂ + C₃": "",
  "C_total = C₁ × C₂ / (C₁ + C₂)": "",
  "C_total = C₁ − C₂ always": "",
  "Capacitors in series combine using the reciprocal formula: 1/C_total = 1/C₁ + 1/C₂ + ... The total capacitance is always less than the smallest individual capacitance.": "",
  "What happens to stored energy if voltage across a capacitor is doubled?": "",
  "Energy doubles to twice the original value": "",
  "Energy quadruples to four times the original": "",
  "Energy stays exactly the same as before": "",
  "Energy is reduced to half the original value": "",
  "Since U = ½CV², doubling V gives U = ½C(2V)² = ½C × 4V² = 4 × ½CV². The energy quadruples.": "",
  "What is the formula for parallel plate capacitance?": "",
  "C = ε₀d/A": "",
  "C = ε₀A/d": "",
  "C = ε₀A × d": "",
  "C = A/(ε₀d)": "",
  "For a parallel plate capacitor, C = ε₀A/d, where A is plate area, d is plate separation, and ε₀ is the permittivity of free space.": "",
  "What is a 'capacitor' in electronics?": "",
  "A device that stores electrical energy using two conducting plates separated by an insulator": "",
  "A device that converts alternating current into direct current for electronic circuits": "",
  "A device that measures the amount of electric charge flowing through a wire per second": "",
  "A device that increases the voltage in a circuit by using electromagnetic induction": "",
  "A capacitor consists of two conducting plates separated by an insulating material (dielectric). It stores electrical energy in the electric field between the plates.": "",
  "What is a 'dielectric' material?": "",
  "A conducting material that allows charges to flow freely between capacitor plates": "",
  "An insulating material placed between capacitor plates that increases capacitance": "",
  "A magnetic material that stores energy in a magnetic field around a coil": "",
  "A semiconductor material used to control current flow in transistor circuits": "",
  "A dielectric is an insulating material placed between capacitor plates. It increases capacitance by reducing the effective electric field, allowing more charge to be stored for a given voltage.": "",
  "What does 'capacitance' measure about a capacitor?": "",
  "How much current the capacitor allows to flow through its plates directly": "",
  "How much charge the capacitor can store per unit of voltage applied": "",
  "How much voltage the capacitor produces when fully charged and disconnected": "",
  "How quickly the capacitor discharges all of its stored energy through a wire": "",
  "Capacitance (C = Q/V) measures the amount of charge a capacitor stores per volt of applied voltage. Higher capacitance means more charge stored for the same voltage.": "",
  "What does the 'Farad' (F) represent?": "",
  "One coulomb of charge stored per one volt of applied potential difference": "",
  "One joule of energy stored per one ampere of current flowing into a device": "",
  "One volt of potential difference per one ohm of electrical resistance": "",
  "One ampere of current flowing per one second through a conducting wire": "",
  "One Farad means one coulomb of charge is stored per one volt of potential difference: 1 F = 1 C/V. One Farad is extremely large; most practical capacitors are in microfarads or picofarads.": "",
  "What does 'charging' a capacitor mean?": "",
  "Allowing charge to build up on the plates by connecting to a voltage source": "",
  "Removing all stored charge from the plates by shorting them together": "",
  "Increasing the physical distance between the two plates of the capacitor": "",
  "Replacing the dielectric material with a different insulating material type": "",
  "Charging a capacitor means connecting it to a voltage source so that charge accumulates on the plates — positive on one plate and negative on the other — until the voltage across the capacitor equals the source voltage.": "",
  "What does 'discharging' a capacitor mean?": "",
  "Connecting a voltage source to increase the charge stored on the plates": "",
  "Allowing the stored charge to flow off the plates through an external circuit": "",
  "Physically separating the two plates of the capacitor further apart": "",
  "Permanently destroying the capacitor by applying too much voltage to it": "",
  "Discharging is when the stored charge flows off the plates through an external circuit, converting the stored electrical energy into other forms (heat, light, etc.) until the voltage drops to zero.": "",
  "What does 'plate area' refer to in a parallel plate capacitor?": "",
  "The overlapping surface area of one conducting plate facing the other plate": "",
  "The total volume of space between the two conducting plates of the capacitor": "",
  "The thickness of each conducting plate measured from front to back": "",
  "The distance separating the two plates from each other in the capacitor": "",
  "Plate area (A) is the area of one plate that faces the other. C = ε₀A/d shows that increasing plate area increases capacitance proportionally.": "",
  "What is 'plate separation' in a parallel plate capacitor?": "",
  "The overlapping area of the two plates that face each other directly": "",
  "The total thickness of the dielectric material inside the capacitor": "",
  "The distance between the two parallel conducting plates of the capacitor": "",
  "The voltage difference between the positive and negative plates overall": "",
  "Plate separation (d) is the distance between the two parallel conducting plates. C = ε₀A/d shows that decreasing plate separation increases capacitance.": "",
  "What is the 'dielectric constant' of a material?": "",
  "The factor by which a dielectric increases the capacitance compared to vacuum": "",
  "The electric field strength needed to break down the dielectric material": "",
  "The current that flows through the dielectric when voltage is first applied": "",
  "The temperature at which the dielectric material stops being an insulator": "",
  "The dielectric constant (κ) is the factor by which a dielectric material increases capacitance compared to vacuum: C = κε₀A/d. For vacuum, κ = 1; for other materials, κ > 1.": "",
  "What does 'energy density' mean for a capacitor's electric field?": "",
  "The energy stored per unit volume of the electric field between the plates": "",
  "The total energy stored by the capacitor divided by its total plate area": "",
  "The maximum voltage the capacitor can handle before it fails permanently": "",
  "The rate at which the capacitor discharges its energy through a resistance": "",
  "Energy density is the energy stored per unit volume in the electric field: u = ½ε₀E². It describes how concentrated the stored energy is in the region between the plates.": "",
  "A student connects a 10 μF capacitor to a 5 V battery. How much charge is stored?": "",
  "The stored charge is 2 μC on each plate": "",
  "The stored charge is 50 μC on each plate": "",
  "The stored charge is 15 μC on each plate": "",
  "The stored charge is 0.5 μC on each plate": "",
  "Q = CV = 10 μF × 5 V = 50 μC. Each plate holds 50 μC of charge (positive on one, negative on the other).": "",
  "A student has two 6 μF capacitors. They connect them in parallel. What is the total capacitance?": "",
  "The total capacitance is 3 μF": "",
  "The total capacitance is 12 μF": "",
  "The total capacitance is 6 μF": "",
  "The total capacitance is 36 μF": "",
  "In parallel: C_total = C₁ + C₂ = 6 + 6 = 12 μF.": "",
  "A student has two 6 μF capacitors. They connect them in series. What is the total capacitance?": "",
  "In series: 1/C_total = 1/6 + 1/6 = 2/6, so C_total = 3 μF.": "",
  "A student doubles the plate area of a parallel plate capacitor. What happens to the capacitance?": "",
  "The capacitance stays the same as before": "",
  "The capacitance doubles to twice the original": "",
  "The capacitance is cut in half from the original": "",
  "The capacitance quadruples to four times original": "",
  "Since C = ε₀A/d, doubling the plate area A doubles the capacitance. Capacitance is directly proportional to plate area.": "",
  "A student inserts a plastic sheet (dielectric) between the plates of a charged, disconnected capacitor. What happens to the voltage?": "",
  "The voltage increases because the dielectric adds energy to the system": "",
  "The voltage decreases because the dielectric reduces the electric field": "",
  "The voltage stays the same because the charge is fixed on the plates": "",
  "The voltage drops to zero because the dielectric is an insulating material": "",
  "For a disconnected capacitor, charge Q is fixed. The dielectric increases C. Since V = Q/C, increasing C decreases V. The voltage drops because the dielectric reduces the electric field between plates.": "",
  "A student uses a camera flash that relies on a capacitor. Why is a capacitor used instead of the battery directly?": "",
  "The capacitor produces a brighter color of light than the battery can": "",
  "The capacitor can release stored energy very quickly for a bright flash": "",
  "The capacitor is smaller and lighter than any battery of the same size": "",
  "The capacitor converts electrical energy into light more efficiently always": "",
  "A capacitor can discharge its stored energy extremely rapidly, providing the high burst of power needed for a camera flash. A battery alone cannot deliver energy fast enough for the brief, intense flash.": "",
  "In a lab, a student charges a capacitor to 10 V and measures the energy stored. They then charge it to 20 V. How does the energy compare?": "",
  "The energy at 20 V is twice the energy at 10 V": "",
  "The energy at 20 V is four times the energy at 10 V": "",
  "The energy at 20 V is the same as the energy at 10 V": "",
  "The energy at 20 V is eight times the energy at 10 V": "",
  "U = ½CV². Doubling V from 10 to 20 V: U₂ = ½C(20)² = ½C(400), while U₁ = ½C(10)² = ½C(100). U₂/U₁ = 4. Energy is four times greater.": "",
  "A student builds a circuit with a capacitor and a resistor. When the switch is closed, the capacitor charges. What happens to the charging current over time?": "",
  "The current stays constant until the capacitor is fully charged": "",
  "The current gradually decreases as the capacitor charges up to full": "",
  "The current gradually increases as more charge builds up on the plates": "",
  "The current oscillates back and forth between the plates during charging": "",
  "As the capacitor charges, the voltage across it increases, reducing the voltage across the resistor. This means the current (V_R/R) decreases exponentially over time until the capacitor is fully charged and current drops to zero.": "",
  "A student wonders why capacitors in electronic devices are often labeled in microfarads rather than farads. Why?": "",
  "One farad is an extremely large capacitance value for most practical applications": "",
  "The farad is an outdated unit that has been replaced by the microfarad unit": "",
  "Microfarads are easier to measure with standard laboratory equipment": "",
  "Farads only apply to theoretical capacitors and not real world components": "",
  "One farad is an enormous capacitance — it would require impractically large plates. Most everyday capacitors range from picofarads (pF) to microfarads (μF), which is why these smaller units are used.": "",
